  "prompt": "Can a private company take loan from another private company as per provision of Companies Act 2013?",
  "response": "Yes, a private company can take a loan from another private company under the provisions of the Companies Act, 2013. However, there are certain conditions and restrictions that need to be followed:\n\n1. Board Resolution: The borrowing company must pass a board resolution authorizing the loan.\n\n2. Compliance with Section 185 and 186:\n- Section 185 restricts loans to directors and related parties\n- Section 186 governs loans and investments by companies\n\n3. Disclosure Requirements:\n- The loan must be disclosed in the company's financial statements\n- Particulars of loans must be reported in the annual return\n\n4. Interest Rate: There are no specific restrictions on the interest rate, but it should be at arm's length and market-reasonable.\n\n5. Additional Considerations:\n- The borrowing should be for bonafide business purposes\n- The loan agreement should specify terms and conditions\n- Compliance with RBI regulations (if applicable)\n\n6. Limitations:\n- Loans beyond specified limits require shareholders' approval\n- Some restrictions apply for inter-corporate loans\n\nImportant: While the Companies Act allows such loans, companies must ensure full compliance with all relevant provisions and regulations.",
